#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:5
msgid "Emscripten Compiler Frontend (emcc)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:7
msgid ""
"The Emscripten Compiler Frontend (``emcc``) is used to call the Emscripten "
"compiler from the command line. It is effectively a drop-in replacement for "
"a standard compiler like *gcc* or *clang*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:11
msgid "Command line syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:17
msgid ""
"(Note that you will need ``./emcc`` if you want to run emcc from your "
"current directory.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:19
msgid ""
"The input file(s) can be either source code files that *Clang* can handle (C "
"or C++), object files (produced by `emcc -c`), or LLVM assembly files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:24
msgid "Arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:26
msgid ""
"Most `clang options <http://linux.die.net/man/1/clang>`_ will work, as will "
"`gcc options <https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Option-Summary.html#Option-"
"Summary>`_, for example: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:35
msgid ""
"To see the full list of *Clang* options supported on the version of *Clang* "
"used by Emscripten, run ``clang --help``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:37
msgid "Options that are modified or new in *emcc* are listed below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:43
msgid "``-O0``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:44
msgid ""
"[compile+link] No optimizations (default). This is the recommended setting "
"for starting to port a project, as it includes various assertions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:47
msgid ""
"This and other optimization settings are meaningful both during compile and "
"during link. During compile it affects LLVM optimizations, and during link "
"it affects final optimization of the code in Binaryen as well as "
"optimization of the JS. (For fast incremental builds ``-O0`` is best, while "
"for release you should link with something higher.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:55
msgid "``-O1``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:56
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Simple optimizations. During the compile step these include "
"LLVM ``-O1`` optimizations. During the link step this omits various runtime "
"assertions in JS that `-O0` would include."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:61
msgid "``-O2``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:62
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Like ``-O1``, but enables more optimizations. During link "
"this will also enable various JavaScript optimizations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:65
msgid ""
"These JavaScript optimizations can reduce code size by removing things that "
"the compiler does not see being used, in particular, parts of the runtime "
"may be stripped if they are not exported on the ``Module`` object. The "
"compiler is aware of code in :ref:`--pre-js <emcc-pre-js>` and :ref:`--post-"
"js <emcc-post-js>`, so you can safely use the runtime from there. "
"Alternatively, you can use ``EXPORTED_RUNTIME_METHODS``, see `src/settings."
"js <https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/main/src/settings."
"js>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:69
msgid "``-O3``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:70
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Like ``-O2``, but with additional optimizations that may take "
"longer to run and may increase code size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:73
msgid "This is a good setting for a release build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:77
msgid "``-Og``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:78
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Like ``-O1``, with an additional flag to extend the liveness "
"of variables for improved debugging. In future versions, additional "
"optimizations might also be disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:84
msgid "``-Os``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:85
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Like ``-O3``, but focuses more on code size (and may make "
"tradeoffs with speed). This can affect both Wasm and JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:90
msgid "``-Oz``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:91
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Like ``-Os``, but reduces code size even further, and may "
"take longer to run. This can affect both Wasm and JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:94
msgid "For more tips on optimizing your code, see :ref:`Optimizing-Code`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:98
msgid "``-sOPTION[=VALUE]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:99
msgid ""
"[different OPTIONs affect at different stages, most at link time] Emscripten "
"build options. For the available options, see `src/settings.js <https://"
"github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/main/src/settings.js>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:102
msgid "If no value is specified it will default to ``1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:104
msgid ""
"It is possible, with boolean options, to use the ``NO_`` prefix to reverse "
"their meaning. For example, ``-sEXIT_RUNTIME=0`` is the same as ``-"
"sNO_EXIT_RUNTIME=1`` and vice versa.  This is not recommended in most cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:106
msgid "Lists can be specified as comma separated strings:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:112
msgid ""
"We also support older list formats that involve more quoting.  Lists can be "
"specified with or without quotes around each element and with or without "
"brackets around the list.  For example, all the following are equivalent:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:120
msgid ""
"For lists that include brackets or quote, you need quotation marks (\") "
"around the list in most shells (to avoid errors being raised). Two examples "
"are shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:127
msgid ""
"You can also specify that the value of an option will be read from a file. "
"For example, the following will set ``EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS`` based on the "
"contents of the file at **path/to/file**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:135
msgid ""
"In this case the file should contain a list of symbols, one per line.  For "
"legacy use cases JSON-formatted files are also supported: e.g. "
"``[\"_func1\", \"func2\"]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:136
msgid "The specified file path must be absolute, not relative."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:137
msgid ""
"The file may contain comments where the first character of the line is "
"``'#'``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:140
msgid ""
"Options can be specified as a single argument with or without a space "
"between the ``-s`` and option name.  e.g. ``-sFOO`` or ``-s FOO``. It's "
"`highly recommended <https://emscripten.org/docs/getting_started/FAQ."
"html#how-do-i-specify-s-options-in-a-cmake-project>`_ you use the notation "
"without space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:146
msgid "``-g``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:147
msgid "[compile+link] Preserve debug information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:150
msgid ""
"When compiling to object files, this is the same as in *Clang* and *gcc*, it "
"adds DWARF debug information to the object files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:152
msgid "When linking, this is equivalent to :ref:`-g3 <emcc-g3>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:156
msgid "``-gseparate-dwarf[=FILENAME]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:157
msgid ""
"[same as -g3 if passed at compile time, otherwise applies at link] Preserve "
"debug information, but in a separate file on the side. This is the same as "
"``-g``, but the main file will contain no debug info. Instead, debug info "
"will be present in a file on the side, in ``FILENAME`` if provided, "
"otherwise the same as the Wasm file but with suffix ``.debug.wasm``. While "
"the main file contains no debug info, it does contain a URL to where the "
"debug file is, so that devtools can find it. You can use ``-"
"sSEPARATE_DWARF_URL=URL`` to customize that location (this is useful if you "
"want to host it on a different server, for example)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:169
msgid "``-gsplit-dwarf``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:170
msgid ""
"Enable debug fission, which creates split DWARF object files alongside the "
"wasm object files. This option must be used together with ``-c``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:175
msgid "``-gsource-map[=inline]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:176
msgid ""
"[compile+link] [same as -g3 if passed at compile time, otherwise applies at "
"link] Generate a source map using LLVM debug information (which must be "
"present in object files, i.e., they should have been compiled with ``-g`` or "
"``-gsource-map``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:182
msgid ""
"When this option is provided, the **.wasm** file is updated to have a "
"``sourceMappingURL`` section. The resulting URL will have format: ``<base-"
"url>`` + ``<wasm-file-name>`` + ``.map``. ``<base-url>`` defaults to being "
"empty (which means the source map is served from the same directory as the "
"Wasm file). It can be changed using :ref:`--source-map-base <emcc-source-map-"
"base>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:188
msgid ""
"Path substitution can be applied to the referenced sources using the ``-"
"sSOURCE_MAP_PREFIXES`` (:ref:`link <source_map_prefixes>`). If ``inline`` is "
"specified, the sources content is embedded in the source map (in this case "
"you don't need path substitution, but it comes with the cost of having a "
"large source map file)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:196
msgid "``-g<level>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:197
msgid ""
"[compile+link] If used at compile time, adds progressively more DWARF "
"information to the object file, according to the underlying behavior of "
"clang. If used at link time, controls the level of debuggability overall. "
"Each level builds on the previous one:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:205
msgid "``-g0``: Make no effort to keep code debuggable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:210
msgid "``-g1``: Preserve whitespace in JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:215
msgid ""
"``-g2``: Also preserve function names in compiled code (via the wasm name "
"section)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:220
msgid ""
"``-g3``: Also keep LLVM debug info (DWARF) if there is any in the object "
"files (this is the same as :ref:`-g <emcc-g>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:224
msgid "``--profiling``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:225
msgid ""
"[link] Make the output suitable for profiling. This means including function "
"names in the wasm and JS output, and preserving whitespace in the JS output. "
"It does not affect optimizations (to ensure that performance profiles "
"reflect production builds). Currently this is the same as ``-g2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:232
msgid "``--profiling-funcs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:233
msgid ""
"[link] Preserve wasm function names as in ``--profiling``, but otherwise "
"minify whitespace and names as we normally do in optimized builds. This is "
"useful if you want to look at profiler results based on function names, but "
"do *not* intend to read the emitted code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:236
msgid "``--tracing``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:237
msgid "[link] Enable the :ref:`Emscripten Tracing API <trace-h>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:240
msgid "``--reproduce=<file.tar>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:241
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Write tar file containing inputs and command to reproduce "
"invocation.  When sharing this file be aware that it will any object files, "
"source files and libraries that that were passed to the compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:248
msgid "``--emit-symbol-map``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:249
msgid ""
"[link] Save a map file between function indexes in the Wasm and function "
"names. By storing the names on a file on the side, you can avoid shipping "
"the names, and can still reconstruct meaningful stack traces by translating "
"the indexes back to the names. This is a simpler format than source maps, "
"but less detailed because it only describes function names and not source "
"locations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:256
msgid ""
"When used with ``-sWASM=2``, two symbol files are created. ``[name].js."
"symbols`` (with WASM symbols) and ``[name].wasm.js.symbols`` (with ASM.js "
"symbols)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:260
msgid "``--emit-minification-map <file>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:261
msgid ""
"[link] In cases where emscripten performs import/export minification this "
"option can be used to output a file that maps minified names back to their "
"original names.  The format of this file is single line per import/export of "
"the form ``<minname>:<origname>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:269
msgid "``-flto``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:270
msgid "[compile+link] Enables link-time optimizations (LTO)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:275
msgid "``--closure 0|1|2``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:276
msgid "[link] Runs the :term:`Closure Compiler`. Possible values are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:279
msgid "``0``: No closure compiler (default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:280
msgid ""
"``1``: Run closure compiler. This greatly reduces the size of the support "
"JavaScript code (everything but the WebAssembly or asm.js). Note that this "
"increases compile time significantly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:281
msgid ""
"``2``: Run closure compiler on *all* the emitted code, even on **asm.js** "
"output in **asm.js** mode. This can further reduce code size, but does "
"prevent a significant amount of **asm.js** optimizations, so it is not "
"recommended unless you want to reduce code size at all costs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:285
msgid ""
"Consider using ``-sMODULARIZE`` when using closure, as it minifies globals "
"to names that might conflict with others in the global scope. ``MODULARIZE`` "
"puts all the output into a function (see ``src/settings.js``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:286
msgid ""
"Closure will minify the name of `Module` itself, by default! Using "
"``MODULARIZE`` will solve that as well. Another solution is to make sure a "
"global variable called `Module` already exists before the closure-compiled "
"code runs, because then it will reuse that variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:288
msgid "``--closure-args=<args>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:289
msgid ""
"[link] Pass arguments to the :term:`Closure compiler`. This is an "
"alternative to ``EMCC_CLOSURE_ARGS``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:292
msgid ""
"For example, one might want to pass an externs file to avoid minifying JS "
"functions defined in ``--pre-js`` or ``--post-js`` files. To pass to Closure "
"the ``externs.js`` file containing those public APIs that should not be "
"minified, one would add the flag: ``--closure-args=--externs=path/to/externs."
"js``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:298
msgid "``--pre-js <file>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:299
msgid ""
"[link] Specify a file whose contents are added before the emitted code and "
"optimized together with it. Note that this might not literally be the very "
"first thing in the JS output, for example if ``MODULARIZE`` is used (see "
"``src/settings.js``). If you want that, you can just prepend to the output "
"from emscripten; the benefit of ``--pre-js`` is that it optimizes the code "
"with the rest of the emscripten output, which allows better dead code "
"elimination and minification, and it should only be used for that purpose. "
"In particular, ``--pre-js`` code should not alter the main output from "
"emscripten in ways that could confuse the optimizer, such as using ``--pre-"
"js`` + ``--post-js`` to put all the output in an inner function scope (see "
"``MODULARIZE`` for that)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:302
msgid ""
"`--pre-js` (but not `--post-js`) is also useful for specifying things on the "
"``Module`` object, as it appears before the JS looks at ``Module`` (for "
"example, you can define ``Module['print']`` there)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:306
msgid "``--post-js <file>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:307
msgid "[link] Like ``--pre-js``, but emits a file *after* the emitted code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:310
msgid "``--extern-pre-js <file>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:311
msgid ""
"[link] Specify a file whose contents are prepended to the JavaScript output. "
"This file is prepended to the final JavaScript output, *after* all other "
"work has been done, including optimization, optional ``MODULARIZE``-ation, "
"instrumentation like ``SAFE_HEAP``, etc. This is the same as prepending this "
"file after ``emcc`` finishes running, and is just a convenient way to do "
"that. (For comparison, ``--pre-js`` and ``--post-js`` optimize the code "
"together with everything else, keep it in the same scope if running "
"`MODULARIZE`, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:321
msgid "``--extern-post-js <file>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:322
msgid "[link] Like ``--extern-pre-js``, but appends to the end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:327
msgid "``--embed-file <file>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:328
msgid ""
"[link] Specify a file (with path) to embed inside the generated WebAssembly "
"module. The path is relative to the current directory at compile time. If a "
"directory is passed here, its entire contents will be embedded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:333
msgid ""
"For example, if the command includes ``--embed-file dir/file.dat``, then "
"``dir/file.dat`` must exist relative to the directory where you run *emcc*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:336
msgid ""
"Embedding files is generally more efficient than :ref:`preloading <emcc-"
"preload-file>` as it avoids copying the file data at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:339
msgid ""
"For more information about the ``--embed-file`` options, see :ref:`packaging-"
"files`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:344
msgid "``--preload-file <name>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:345
msgid ""
"[link] Specify a file to preload before running the compiled code "
"asynchronously. The path is relative to the current directory at compile "
"time. If a directory is passed here, its entire contents will be embedded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:350
msgid ""
"Preloaded files are stored in **filename.data**, where **filename.html** is "
"the main file you are compiling to. To run your code, you will need both the "
"**.html** and the **.data**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:354
msgid ""
"This option is similar to :ref:`--embed-file <emcc-embed-file>`, except that "
"it is only relevant when generating HTML (it uses asynchronous binary :term:"
"`XHRs <XHR>`), or JavaScript that will be used in a web page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:358
msgid ""
"*emcc* runs `tools/file_packager <https://github.com/emscripten-core/"
"emscripten/blob/main/tools/file_packager.py>`_ to do the actual packaging of "
"embedded and preloaded files. You can run the file packager yourself if you "
"want (see :ref:`packaging-files-file-packager`). You should then put the "
"output of the file packager in an emcc ``--pre-js``, so that it executes "
"before your main compiled code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:365
msgid ""
"For more information about the ``--preload-file`` options, see :ref:"
"`packaging-files`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:370
msgid "``--exclude-file <name>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:371
msgid ""
"[link] Files and directories to be excluded from :ref:`--embed-file <emcc-"
"embed-file>` and :ref:`--preload-file <emcc-preload-file>`. Wildcards (*) "
"are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:374
msgid "``--use-preload-plugins``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:375
msgid ""
"[link] Tells the file packager to run preload plugins on the files as they "
"are loaded. This performs tasks like decoding images and audio using the "
"browser's codecs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:380
msgid "``--shell-file <path>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:381
msgid ""
"[link] The path name to a skeleton HTML file used when generating HTML "
"output. The shell file used needs to have this token inside it: "
"``{{{ SCRIPT }}}``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:386
msgid ""
"See `html/shell.html <https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/"
"main/html/shell.html>`_ and `html/shell_minimal.html <https://github.com/"
"emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/main/html/shell_minimal.html>`_ for examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:387
msgid ""
"This argument is ignored if a target other than HTML is specified using the "
"``-o`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:391
msgid "``--source-map-base <base-url>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:392
msgid ""
"[link] The base URL for the location where WebAssembly source maps will be "
"published. Must be used with :ref:`-gsource-map <emcc-gsource-map>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:398
msgid "``--minify 0``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:399
msgid ""
"[same as -g1 if passed at compile time, otherwise applies at link] Identical "
"to ``-g1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:402
msgid "``--js-transform <cmd>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:403
msgid ""
"[link] Specifies a ``<cmd>`` to be called on the generated code before it is "
"optimized. This lets you modify the JavaScript, for example adding or "
"removing some code, in a way that those modifications will be optimized "
"together with the generated code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:406
msgid ""
"``<cmd>`` will be called with the file name of the generated code as a "
"parameter. To modify the code, you can read the original data and then "
"append to it or overwrite it with the modified data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:408
msgid ""
"``<cmd>`` is interpreted as a space-separated list of arguments, for "
"example, ``<cmd>`` of **python processor.py** will cause a Python script to "
"be run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:412
msgid "``--bind``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:413
msgid ""
"[link] Links against embind library.  Deprecated: Use ``-lembind`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:418
msgid "``--embind-emit-tsd <path>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:419
msgid ""
"[link] Generates TypeScript definition file.  Deprecated: Use ``--emit-tsd`` "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:424
msgid "``--emit-tsd <path>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:425
msgid ""
"[link] Generate a TypeScript definition file for the emscripten module. The "
"definition file will include exported Wasm functions, runtime exports, and "
"exported embind bindings (if used). In order to generate bindings from "
"embind, the program will be instrumented and run in node."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:431
msgid "``--ignore-dynamic-linking``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:432
msgid ""
"[link] Tells the compiler to ignore dynamic linking (the user will need to "
"manually link to the shared libraries later on)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:435
msgid ""
"Normally *emcc* will simply link in code from the dynamic library as though "
"it were statically linked, which will fail if the same dynamic library is "
"linked more than once. With this option, dynamic linking is ignored, which "
"allows the build system to proceed without errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:439
msgid "``--js-library <lib>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:440
msgid ""
"[link] A JavaScript library to use in addition to those in Emscripten's core "
"libraries (src/library_*)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:445
msgid "``-v``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:446
msgid "[general] Turns on verbose output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:449
msgid ""
"This will print the internal sub-commands run by emscripten as well as ``-"
"v`` to *Clang*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:452
msgid ""
"``emcc -v`` is a useful tool for diagnosing errors. It works with or without "
"other arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:454
msgid "``--check``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:455
msgid ""
"[general] Runs Emscripten's internal sanity checks and reports any issues "
"with the current configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:461
msgid "``--cache <directory>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:462
msgid ""
"[general] Sets the directory to use as the Emscripten cache. The Emscripten "
"cache is used to store pre-built versions of ``libc``, ``libcxx`` and other "
"libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:467
msgid ""
"If using this in combination with ``--clear-cache``, be sure to specify this "
"argument first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:470
msgid ""
"The Emscripten cache defaults to ``emscripten/cache`` but can be overridden "
"using the ``EM_CACHE`` environment variable or ``CACHE`` config setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:475
msgid "``--clear-cache``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:476
msgid ""
"[general] Manually clears the cache of compiled Emscripten system libraries "
"(libc++, libc++abi, libc)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:480
msgid ""
"This is normally handled automatically, but if you update LLVM in-place "
"(instead of having a different directory for a new version), the caching "
"mechanism can get confused. Clearing the cache can fix weird problems "
"related to cache incompatibilities, like *Clang* failing to link with "
"library files. This also clears other cached data. After the cache is "
"cleared, this process will exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:487
msgid ""
"By default this will also clear any download ports since the ports directory "
"is usually within the cache directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:492
msgid "``--use-port=<port>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:493
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Use the specified port. If you need to use more than one port "
"you can use this option multiple times (ex: ``--use-port=sdl2 --use-"
"port=bzip2``). A port can have options separated by ``:`` (ex: ``--use-"
"port=sdl2_image:formats=png,jpg``). To use an  external port, you provide "
"the path to the port directly (ex: ``--use-port=/path/to/my_port.py``). To "
"get more information about a port, use the ``help`` option (ex: ``--use-"
"port=sdl2_image:help``). To get the list of available ports, use ``--show-"
"ports``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:505
msgid "``--clear-ports``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:506
msgid ""
"[general] Manually clears the local copies of ports from the Emscripten "
"Ports repos (sdl2, etc.). This also clears the cache, to remove their builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:510
msgid ""
"You should only need to do this if a problem happens and you want all ports "
"that you use to be downloaded and built from scratch. After this operation "
"is complete, this process will exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:516
msgid "``--show-ports``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:517
msgid ""
"[general] Shows the list of available projects in the Emscripten Ports "
"repos. After this operation is complete, this process will exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:520
msgid "``-Wwarn-absolute-paths``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:521
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Enables warnings about the use of absolute paths in ``-I`` "
"and ``-L`` command line directives. This is used to warn against "
"unintentional use of absolute paths, which is sometimes dangerous when "
"referring to nonportable local system headers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:526
msgid "``--emrun``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:527
msgid ""
"[link] Enables the generated output to be aware of the :ref:`emrun <Running-"
"html-files-with-emrun>` command line tool. This allows ``stdout``, "
"``stderr`` and ``exit(returncode)`` capture when running the generated "
"application through *emrun*. (This enables `EXIT_RUNTIME=1`, allowing normal "
"runtime exiting with return code passing.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:530
msgid "``--cpuprofiler``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:531
msgid ""
"[link] Embeds a simple CPU profiler onto the generated page. Use this to "
"perform cursory interactive performance profiling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:534
msgid "``--memoryprofiler``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:535
msgid ""
"[link] Embeds a memory allocation tracker onto the generated page. Use this "
"to profile the application usage of the Emscripten HEAP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:538
msgid "``--threadprofiler``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:539
msgid ""
"[link] Embeds a thread activity profiler onto the generated page. Use this "
"to profile the application usage of pthreads when targeting multithreaded "
"builds (-pthread)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:544
msgid "``--em-config <path>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:545
msgid ""
"[general] Specifies the location of the **.emscripten** configuration file.  "
"If not specified emscripten will search for ``.emscripten`` first in the "
"emscripten directory itself, and then in the user's home directory (``~/."
"emscripten``). This can be overridden using the ``EM_CONFIG`` environment "
"variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:551
msgid "``--valid-abspath <path>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:552
msgid ""
"[compile+link] Note an allowed absolute path, which we should not warn about "
"(absolute include paths normally are warned about, since they may refer to "
"the local system headers etc. which we need to avoid when cross-compiling)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:559
msgid "``-o <target>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:560
msgid ""
"[link] When linking an executable, the ``target`` file name extension "
"defines the output type to be generated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:563
msgid ""
"<name> **.js** : JavaScript (+ separate **<name>.wasm** file if emitting "
"WebAssembly). (default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:564
msgid ""
"<name> **.mjs** : ES6 JavaScript module (+ separate **<name>.wasm** file if "
"emitting WebAssembly)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:565
msgid ""
"<name> **.html** : HTML + separate JavaScript file (**<name>.js**; + "
"separate **<name>.wasm** file if emitting WebAssembly)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:566
msgid ""
"<name> **.wasm** : WebAssembly without JavaScript support code (\"standalone "
"Wasm\"; this enables ``STANDALONE_WASM``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:568
msgid ""
"These rules only apply when linking.  When compiling to object code (See `-"
"c` below) the name of the output file is irrelevant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:571
msgid ""
"Note: Linking to a file with no extension (or a file ending in ``.out``, "
"like ``a.out``) will cause the generated JavaScript file to be exectuable, "
"and include a ``#!`` line to make it runnable directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:577
msgid "``-c``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:578
msgid ""
"[compile] Tells *emcc* to emit an object file which can then be linked with "
"other object files to produce an executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:581
msgid "``--output-eol windows|linux``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:582
msgid ""
"[link] Specifies the line ending to generate for the text files that are "
"outputted. If \"--output-eol windows\" is passed, the final output files "
"will have Windows ``\\r\\n`` line endings in them. With \"--output-eol "
"linux\", the final generated files will be written with Unix ``\\n`` line "
"endings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:585
msgid "``--cflags``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:586
msgid ""
"[other] Prints out the flags ``emcc`` would pass to ``clang`` to compile "
"source code to object form. You can use this to invoke clang yourself, and "
"then run ``emcc`` on those outputs just for the final linking+conversion to "
"JS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:592
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:593
msgid "*emcc* is affected by several environment variables, as listed below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:595
msgid "``EMMAKEN_JUST_CONFIGURE`` [other]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:596
msgid "``EMCC_AUTODEBUG`` [compile+link]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:597
msgid "``EMCC_CFLAGS`` [compile+link]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:598
msgid "``EMCC_CORES`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:599
msgid "``EMCC_DEBUG`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:600
msgid "``EMCC_DEBUG_SAVE`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:601
msgid "``EMCC_FORCE_STDLIBS`` [link]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:602
msgid "``EMCC_ONLY_FORCED_STDLIBS`` [link]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:603
msgid "``EMCC_LOCAL_PORTS`` [compile+link]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:604
msgid ""
"``EMCC_CLOSURE_ARGS`` [link] arguments to be passed to *Closure Compiler*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:605
msgid "``EMCC_STRICT`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:606
msgid "``EMCC_SKIP_SANITY_CHECK`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:607
msgid "``EM_IGNORE_SANITY`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:608
msgid "``EM_CONFIG`` [general]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:609
msgid "``EM_LLVM_ROOT`` [compile+link]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:610
msgid ""
"``_EMCC_CCACHE`` [general] Internal setting that is set to 1 by emsdk when "
"integrating with ccache compiler frontend"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/emcc.rst:612
msgid ""
"Search for 'os.environ' in `emcc.py <https://github.com/emscripten-core/"
"emscripten/blob/main/emcc.py>`_ to see how these are used. The most "
"interesting is possibly ``EMCC_DEBUG``, which forces the compiler to dump "
"its build and temporary files to a temporary directory where they can be "
"reviewed."
msgstr ""

